Introduction to DataFrames¶

The notebook is compiled from different tutorials by Bogumi Kamiski
~ Mousum Dutta

Let's get started by loading the DataFrames package.

In [1]:
using DataFrames, Random

Constructors and conversion¶

Constructors¶

In this section, you'll see many ways to create a DataFrame using the DataFrame() constructor.

First, we could create an empty DataFrame,

In [2]:
DataFrame()
Out[2]:
00 DataFrame

Or we could call the constructor using keyword arguments to add columns to the DataFrame.

In [3]:
DataFrame(A=1:3, B=rand(3), C=randstring.([3,3,3]), fixed=1)
Out[3]:
34 DataFrame
RowABCfixed
Int64Float64StringInt64
110.452964Lye1
220.574186hgH1
330.729346JOk1

note in column :fixed that scalars get automatically broadcasted.

We can create a DataFrame from a dictionary, in which case keys from the dictionary will be sorted to create the DataFrame columns.

In [4]:
x = Dict("A" => [1,2], "B" => [true, false], "C" => ['a', 'b'], "fixed" => Ref([1,1]))
DataFrame(x)
Out[4]:
24 DataFrame
RowABCfixed
Int64BoolCharArray
11truea[1, 1]
22falseb[1, 1]

This time we used Ref to protect a vector from being treated as a column and forcing broadcasting it into every row of :fixed column (note that the [1,1] vector is aliased in each row).

Rather than explicitly creating a dictionary first, as above, we could pass DataFrame arguments with the syntax of dictionary key-value pairs.

Note that in this case, we use Symbols to denote the column names and arguments are not sorted. For example, :A, the symbol, produces A, the name of the first column here:

In [5]:
DataFrame(:A => [1,2], :B => [true, false], :C => ['a', 'b'])
Out[5]:
23 DataFrame
RowABC
Int64BoolChar
11truea
22falseb

Although, in general, using Symbols rather than strings to denote column names is preferred (as it is faster) DataFrames.jl accepts passing strings as column names, so this also works:

In [6]:
DataFrame("A" => [1,2], "B" => [true, false], "C" => ['a', 'b'])
Out[6]:
23 DataFrame
RowABC
Int64BoolChar
11truea
22falseb

You can also pass a vector of pairs, which is useful if it is constructed programatically:

In [7]:
DataFrame([:A => [1,2], :B => [true, false], :C => ['a', 'b'], :fixed => "const"])
Out[7]:
24 DataFrame
RowABCfixed
Int64BoolCharString
11trueaconst
22falsebconst

Here we create a DataFrame from a vector of vectors, and each vector becomes a column.

In [8]:
DataFrame([rand(3) for i in 1:3], :auto)
Out[8]:
33 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3
Float64Float64Float64
10.1871510.4269060.157622
20.1398380.1762630.901357
30.5124140.6782940.787619
In [9]:
DataFrame([rand(3) for i in 1:3], [:x1, :x2, :x3])
Out[9]:
33 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3
Float64Float64Float64
10.1377720.01075140.416007
20.4421350.4698290.562258
30.02494110.2754260.111368
In [10]:
DataFrame([rand(3) for i in 1:3], ["x1", "x2", "x3"])
Out[10]:
33 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3
Float64Float64Float64
10.7539510.189560.649372
20.7000870.405020.346524
30.7335560.6401710.384105

As you can see you either pass a vector of column names as a second argument or :auto in which case column names are generated automatically.

In particular it is not allowed to pass a vector of scalars to DataFrame constructor.

In [11]:
DataFrame([1, 2, 3])

ArgumentError: 'Vector{Int64}' iterates 'Int64' values, which doesn't satisfy the Tables.jl `AbstractRow` interface

Stacktrace:
 [1] invalidtable(#unused#::Vector{Int64}, #unused#::Int64)
   @ Tables C:\Users\user\.julia\packages\Tables\NSGZI\src\tofromdatavalues.jl:41
 [2] iterate
   @ C:\Users\user\.julia\packages\Tables\NSGZI\src\tofromdatavalues.jl:47 [inlined]
 [3] buildcolumns
   @ C:\Users\user\.julia\packages\Tables\NSGZI\src\fallbacks.jl:209 [inlined]
 [4] _columns
   @ C:\Users\user\.julia\packages\Tables\NSGZI\src\fallbacks.jl:274 [inlined]
 [5] columns
   @ C:\Users\user\.julia\packages\Tables\NSGZI\src\fallbacks.jl:258 [inlined]
 [6] DataFrame(x::Vector{Int64}; copycols::Nothing)
   @ DataFrames C:\Users\user\.julia\packages\DataFrames\58MUJ\src\other\tables.jl:57
 [7] DataFrame(x::Vector{Int64})
   @ DataFrames C:\Users\user\.julia\packages\DataFrames\58MUJ\src\other\tables.jl:51
 [8] top-level scope
   @ In[11]:1

Instead use a transposed vector if you have a vector of single values (in this way you effectively pass a two dimensional array to the constructor which is supported the same way as in vector of vectors case).

In [12]:
DataFrame(permutedims([1, 2, 3]), :auto)
Out[12]:
13 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3
Int64Int64Int64
1123

You can also pass a vector of NamedTuples to construct a DataFrame:

In [13]:
v = [(a=1, b=2), (a=3, b=4)]
DataFrame(v)
Out[13]:
22 DataFrame
Rowab
Int64Int64
112
234

Alternatively you can pass a NamedTuple of vectors:

In [14]:
n = (a=1:3, b=11:13)
DataFrame(n)
Out[14]:
32 DataFrame
Rowab
Int64Int64
1111
2212
3313

Here we create a DataFrame from a matrix,

In [15]:
DataFrame(rand(3, 4), :auto)
Out[15]:
34 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3x4
Float64Float64Float64Float64
10.6668220.6298530.2200150.523894
20.5380870.2140970.2113080.715484
30.7389580.2677160.3081830.222669

and here we do the same but also pass column names.

In [16]:
DataFrame(rand(3, 4), Symbol.('a':'d'))
Out[16]:
34 DataFrame
Rowabcd
Float64Float64Float64Float64
10.03261880.817280.5017940.168495
20.2762810.2885470.7629770.663397
30.2522610.7569360.4339630.886909

or

In [17]:
DataFrame(rand(3, 4), string.('a':'d'))
Out[17]:
34 DataFrame
Rowabcd
Float64Float64Float64Float64
10.8405130.5312390.3272440.109567
20.004277230.1693080.2808620.702685
30.774560.8673860.161840.423085

This is how you can create a data frame with no rows, but with predefined columns and their types:

In [18]:
DataFrame(A=Int[], B=Float64[], C=String[])
Out[18]:
03 DataFrame
RowABC
Int64Float64String

Finally, we can create a DataFrame by copying an existing DataFrame.

Note that copy also copies the vectors.

In [19]:
x = DataFrame(a=1:2, b='a':'b')
y = copy(x)
(x === y), isequal(x, y), (x.a == y.a), (x.a === y.a)
Out[19]:
(false, true, true, false)

Calling DataFrame on a DataFrame object works like copy.

In [20]:
x = DataFrame(a=1:2, b='a':'b')
y = DataFrame(x)
(x === y), isequal(x, y), (x.a == y.a), (x.a === y.a)
Out[20]:
(false, true, true, false)

You can avoid copying of columns of a data frame (if it is possible) by passing copycols=false keyword argument:

In [21]:
x = DataFrame(a=1:2, b='a':'b')
y = DataFrame(x, copycols=false)
(x === y), isequal(x, y), (x.a == y.a), (x.a === y.a)
Out[21]:
(false, true, true, true)

The same rule applies to other constructors

In [22]:
a = [1, 2, 3]
df1 = DataFrame(a=a)
df2 = DataFrame(a=a, copycols=false)
df1.a === a, df2.a === a
Out[22]:
(false, true)

You can create a similar uninitialized DataFrame based on an original one:

In [23]:
x = DataFrame(a=1, b=1.0)
Out[23]:
12 DataFrame
Rowab
Int64Float64
111.0
In [24]:
similar(x)
Out[24]:
12 DataFrame
Rowab
Int64Float64
1313801.5e-323

number of rows in a new DataFrame can be passed as a second argument

In [25]:
similar(x, 0)
Out[25]:
02 DataFrame
Rowab
Int64Float64
In [26]:
similar(x, 2)
Out[26]:
22 DataFrame
Rowab
Int64Float64
1321.6e-322
242.0e-323

You can also create a new DataFrame from SubDataFrame or DataFrameRow (discussed in detail later in the tutorial; in particular although DataFrameRow is considered a 1-dimensional object similar to a NamedTuple it gets converted to a 1-row DataFrame for convenience)

In [27]:
sdf = view(x, [1,1], :)
Out[27]:
22 SubDataFrame
Rowab
Int64Float64
111.0
211.0
In [28]:
typeof(sdf)
Out[28]:
SubDataFrame{DataFrame, DataFrames.Index, Vector{Int64}}
In [29]:
DataFrame(sdf)
Out[29]:
22 DataFrame
Rowab
Int64Float64
111.0
211.0
In [30]:
dfr = x[1, :]
Out[30]:
DataFrameRow (2 columns)
Rowab
Int64Float64
111.0
In [31]:
DataFrame(dfr)
Out[31]:
12 DataFrame
Rowab
Int64Float64
111.0

Conversion to a matrix¶

Let's start by creating a DataFrame with two rows and two columns.

In [32]:
x = DataFrame(x=1:2, y=["A", "B"])
Out[32]:
22 DataFrame
Rowxy
Int64String
11A
22B

We can create a matrix by passing this DataFrame to Matrix or Array.

In [33]:
Matrix(x)
Out[33]:
22 Matrix{Any}:
 1  "A"
 2  "B"
In [34]:
Array(x)
Out[34]:
22 Matrix{Any}:
 1  "A"
 2  "B"

This would work even if the DataFrame had some missings:

In [35]:
x = DataFrame(x=1:2, y=[missing,"B"])
Out[35]:
22 DataFrame
Rowxy
Int64String?
11missing
22B
In [36]:
Matrix(x)
Out[36]:
22 Matrix{Any}:
 1  missing
 2  "B"

In the two previous matrix examples, Julia created matrices with elements of type Any. We can see more clearly that the type of matrix is inferred when we pass, for example, a DataFrame of integers to Matrix, creating a 2D Array of Int64s:

In [37]:
x = DataFrame(x=1:2, y=3:4)
Out[37]:
22 DataFrame
Rowxy
Int64Int64
113
224
In [38]:
Matrix(x)
Out[38]:
22 Matrix{Int64}:
 1  3
 2  4

In this next example, Julia correctly identifies that Union is needed to express the type of the resulting Matrix (which contains missings).

In [39]:
x = DataFrame(x=1:2, y=[missing,4])
Out[39]:
22 DataFrame
Rowxy
Int64Int64?
11missing
224
In [40]:
Matrix(x)
Out[40]:
22 Matrix{Union{Missing, Int64}}:
 1   missing
 2  4

Note that we can't force a conversion of missing values to Ints!

In [41]:
Matrix{Int}(x)

ArgumentError: cannot convert a DataFrame containing missing values to Matrix{Int64} (found for column y)

Stacktrace:
 [1] Matrix{Int64}(df::DataFrame)
   @ DataFrames C:\Users\user\.julia\packages\DataFrames\58MUJ\src\abstractdataframe\abstractdataframe.jl:1370
 [2] top-level scope
   @ In[41]:1

Conversion to NamedTuple related tabular structures¶

First define some data frame

In [42]:
x = DataFrame(x=1:2, y=["A", "B"])
Out[42]:
22 DataFrame
Rowxy
Int64String
11A
22B

Now we convert a DataFrame into a NamedTuple of vectors

In [43]:
ct = Tables.columntable(x)
Out[43]:
(x = [1, 2], y = ["A", "B"])

Next we convert it into a vector of NamedTuples

In [44]:
rt = Tables.rowtable(x)
Out[44]:
2-element Vector{NamedTuple{(:x, :y), Tuple{Int64, String}}}:
 (x = 1, y = "A")
 (x = 2, y = "B")

We can perform the conversions back to a DataFrame using a standard constructor call:

In [45]:
DataFrame(ct)
Out[45]:
22 DataFrame
Rowxy
Int64String
11A
22B
In [46]:
DataFrame(rt)
Out[46]:
22 DataFrame
Rowxy
Int64String
11A
22B

Iterating data frame by rows or columns¶

Sometimes it is useful to create a wrapper around a DataFrame that produces its rows or columns.

For iterating columns you can use the eachcol function.

In [47]:
ec = eachcol(x)
Out[47]:
22 DataFrameColumns
Rowxy
Int64String
11A
22B

DataFrameColumns object behaves as a vector (note though it is not AbstractVector)

In [48]:
ec isa AbstractVector
Out[48]:
false
In [49]:
ec[1]
Out[49]:
2-element Vector{Int64}:
 1
 2

but you can also index into it using column names:

In [50]:
ec[:x]
Out[50]:
2-element Vector{Int64}:
 1
 2

similarly eachrow creates a DataFrameRows object that is a vector of its rows

In [51]:
er = eachrow(x)
Out[51]:
22 DataFrameRows
Rowxy
Int64String
11A
22B

DataFrameRows is an AbstractVector

In [52]:
er isa AbstractVector
Out[52]:
true
In [53]:
er[end]
Out[53]:
DataFrameRow (2 columns)
Rowxy
Int64String
22B

Note that both data frame and also DataFrameColumns and DataFrameRows objects are not type stable (they do not know the types of their columns). This is useful to avoid compilation cost if you have very wide data frames with heterogenous column types.

However, often (especially if a data frame is narrows) it is useful to create a lazy iterator that produces NamedTuples for each row of the DataFrame. Its key benefit is that it is type stable (so it is useful when you want to perform some operations in a fast way on a small subset of columns of a DataFrame - this strategy is often used internally by DataFrames.jl package):

In [54]:
nti = Tables.namedtupleiterator(x)
Out[54]:
Tables.NamedTupleIterator{Tables.Schema{(:x, :y), Tuple{Int64, String}}, Tables.RowIterator{NamedTuple{(:x, :y), Tuple{Vector{Int64}, Vector{String}}}}}(Tables.RowIterator{NamedTuple{(:x, :y), Tuple{Vector{Int64}, Vector{String}}}}((x = [1, 2], y = ["A", "B"]), 2))
In [55]:
for row in enumerate(nti)
    @show row
end

row = (1, (x = 1, y = "A"))
row = (2, (x = 2, y = "B"))

similarly to the previous options you can easily convert NamedTupleIterator back to a DataFrame.

In [56]:
DataFrame(nti)
Out[56]:
22 DataFrame
Rowxy
Int64String
11A
22B

Handling of duplicate column names¶

We can pass the makeunique keyword argument to allow passing duplicate names (they get deduplicated)

In [57]:
df = DataFrame(:a=>1, :a=>2, :a_1=>3; makeunique=true)
Out[57]:
13 DataFrame
Rowaa_2a_1
Int64Int64Int64
1123

Otherwise, duplicates are not allowed.

In [58]:
df = DataFrame(:a=>1, :a=>2, :a_1=>3)

ArgumentError: Duplicate variable names: :a. Pass makeunique=true to make them unique using a suffix automatically.

Stacktrace:
 [1] make_unique!(names::Vector{Symbol}, src::Vector{Symbol}; makeunique::Bool)
   @ DataFrames C:\Users\user\.julia\packages\DataFrames\58MUJ\src\other\utils.jl:99
 [2] #make_unique#4
   @ C:\Users\user\.julia\packages\DataFrames\58MUJ\src\other\utils.jl:121 [inlined]
 [3] #Index#7
   @ C:\Users\user\.julia\packages\DataFrames\58MUJ\src\other\index.jl:27 [inlined]
 [4] DataFrame(::Pair{Symbol, Int64}, ::Vararg{Pair{Symbol, Int64}}; makeunique::Bool, copycols::Bool)
   @ DataFrames C:\Users\user\.julia\packages\DataFrames\58MUJ\src\dataframe\dataframe.jl:261
 [5] DataFrame(::Pair{Symbol, Int64}, ::Vararg{Pair{Symbol, Int64}})
   @ DataFrames C:\Users\user\.julia\packages\DataFrames\58MUJ\src\dataframe\dataframe.jl:259
 [6] top-level scope
   @ In[58]:1

Observe that currently nothing is not printed when displaying a DataFrame in Jupyter Notebook:

In [59]:
df = DataFrame(x=[1, nothing], y=[nothing, "a"], z=[missing, "c"])
Out[59]:
23 DataFrame
Rowxyz
UnionUnionString?
11missing
2ac

Finally you can use empty! functions to remove all rows from a data frame:

In [60]:
empty!(df)
Out[60]:
03 DataFrame
Rowxyz
UnionUnionString?
In [61]:
df
Out[61]:
03 DataFrame
Rowxyz
UnionUnionString?

Getting basic information about a data frame¶

Let's start by creating a DataFrame object, x, so that we can learn how to get information on that data frame.

In [62]:
x = DataFrame(A = [1, 2], B = [1.0, missing], C = ["a", "b"])
Out[62]:
23 DataFrame
RowABC
Int64Float64?String
111.0a
22missingb

The standard size function works to get dimensions of the DataFrame,

In [63]:
size(x), size(x, 1), size(x, 2)
Out[63]:
((2, 3), 2, 3)

as well as nrow and ncol from R.

In [64]:
nrow(x), ncol(x)
Out[64]:
(2, 3)

describe gives basic summary statistics of data in your DataFrame (check out the help of describe for information on how to customize shown statistics).

In [65]:
describe(x)
Out[65]:
37 DataFrame
Rowvariablemeanminmedianmaxnmissingeltype
SymbolUnionAnyUnionAnyInt64Type
1A1.511.520Int64
2B1.01.01.01.01Union{Missing, Float64}
3Cab0String

you can limit the columns shown by describe using cols keyword argument

In [66]:
describe(x, cols=1:2)
Out[66]:
27 DataFrame
Rowvariablemeanminmedianmaxnmissingeltype
SymbolFloat64RealFloat64RealInt64Type
1A1.511.520Int64
2B1.01.01.01.01Union{Missing, Float64}

names will return the names of all columns as strings

In [67]:
names(x)
Out[67]:
3-element Vector{String}:
 "A"
 "B"
 "C"

you can also get column names with a given eltype:

In [68]:
names(x, String)
Out[68]:
1-element Vector{String}:
 "C"

use propertynames to get a vector of Symbols:

In [69]:
propertynames(x)
Out[69]:
3-element Vector{Symbol}:
 :A
 :B
 :C

using eltype on eachcol(x) returns element types of columns:

In [70]:
eltype.(eachcol(x))
Out[70]:
3-element Vector{Type}:
 Int64
 Union{Missing, Float64}
 String

Here we create some large DataFrame

In [71]:
y = DataFrame(rand(1:10, 1000, 10), :auto)
Out[71]:
100010 DataFrame
975 rows omitted
Rowx1x2x3x4x5x6x7x8x9x10
Int64Int64Int64Int64Int64Int64Int64Int64Int64Int64

9945835478474
9951599493396

and then we can use first to peek into its first few rows

In [72]:
first(y, 5)
Out[72]:
510 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3x4x5x6x7x8x9x10

Using first and last without number of rows will return a first/last DataFrameRow in the DataFrame

In [74]:
first(y)
Out[74]:
DataFrameRow (10 columns)
Rowx1x2x3x4x5x6x7x8x9x10
Int64Int64Int64Int64Int64Int64Int64Int64Int64Int64
12373357479
In [75]:
last(y)
Out[75]:
DataFrameRow (10 columns)
Rowx1x2x3x4x5x6x7x8x9x10
Int64Int64Int64Int64Int64Int64Int64Int64Int64Int64

Displaying wide data frames¶

Create a wide and tall data frame:

In [76]:
df = DataFrame(rand(100, 200), :auto)
Out[76]:
100200 DataFrame
100 columns and 75 rows omitted
Rowx1x2x3x4x5x6x7x8x9x10x11x12x13x14x15x16x17x18x19x20x21x22x23x24x25x26x27x28x29x30x31x32x33x34x35x36x37x38x39x40x41x42x43x44x45x46x47x48x49x50x51x52x53x54x55x56x57x58x59x60x61x62x63x64x65x66x67x68x69x70x71x72x73x74x75x76x77x78x79x80x81x82x83x84x85x86x87x88x89x90x91x92x93x94x95x96x97x98x99x100⋯

Most elementary get and set operations¶

Given the DataFrame x we have created earlier, here are various ways to grab one of its columns as a Vector.

In [77]:
x
Out[77]:
23 DataFrame
RowABC
Int64Float64?String
111.0a
22missingb
In [78]:
x.A, x[!, 1], x[!, :A] # all get the vector stored in our DataFrame without copying it
Out[78]:
([1, 2], [1, 2], [1, 2])
In [79]:
x."A", x[!, "A"] # the same using string indexing
Out[79]:
([1, 2], [1, 2])
In [80]:
x[:, 1] # note that this creates a copy
Out[80]:
2-element Vector{Int64}:
 1
 2
In [81]:
x[:, 1] === x[:, 1]
Out[81]:
false

To grab one row as a DataFrame, we can index as follows.

In [82]:
x[1:1, :]
Out[82]:
13 DataFrame
RowABC
Int64Float64?String
111.0a
In [83]:
x[1, :] 
# this produces a DataFrameRow which is treated as 1-dimensional object similar to a NamedTuple
Out[83]:
DataFrameRow (3 columns)
RowABC
Int64Float64?String
111.0a

We can grab a single cell or element with the same syntax to grab an element of an array.

In [84]:
x[1, 1]
Out[84]:
1

or a new DataFrame that is a subset of rows and columns

In [85]:
x[1:2, 1:2]
Out[85]:
22 DataFrame
RowAB
Int64Float64?
111.0
22missing

You can also use Regex to select columns and Not from InvertedIndices.jl both to select rows and columns

In [86]:
x[Not(1), r"A"]
Out[86]:
11 DataFrame
RowA
Int64
12
In [87]:
x[!, Not(1)] # ! indicates that underlying columns are not copied
Out[87]:
22 DataFrame
RowBC
Float64?String
11.0a
2missingb
In [88]:
x[:, Not(1)] # : means that the columns will get copied
Out[88]:
22 DataFrame
RowBC
Float64?String
11.0a
2missingb

Assignment of a scalar to a data frame can be done in ranges using broadcasting:

In [89]:
x[1:2, 1:2] .= 1
x
Out[89]:
23 DataFrame
RowABC
Int64Float64?String
111.0a
211.0b

Assignment of a vector of length equal to the number of assigned rows using broadcasting

In [90]:
x[1:2, 1:2] .= [1,2]
x
Out[90]:
23 DataFrame
RowABC
Int64Float64?String
111.0a
222.0b

Assignment or of another data frame of matching size and column names, again using broadcasting:

In [91]:
x[1:2, 1:2] .= DataFrame([5 6; 7 8], [:A, :B])
x
Out[91]:
23 DataFrame
RowABC
Int64Float64?String
156.0a
278.0b

Caution

With df[!, :col] and df.col syntax you get a direct (non copying) access to a column of a data frame. This is potentially unsafe as you can easily corrupt data in the df data frame if you resize, sort, etc. the column obtained in this way. Therefore such access should be used with caution.

Similarly df[!, cols] when cols is a collection of columns produces a new data frame that holds the same (not copied) columns as the source df data frame. Similarly, modifying the data frame obtained via df[!, cols] might cause problems with the consistency of df.

The df[:, :col] and df[:, cols] syntaxes always copy columns so they are safe to use (and should generally be preferred except for performance or memory critical use cases).

Here are examples of how Cols and Between can be used to select columns of a data frame.

In [92]:
x = DataFrame(rand(4, 5), :auto)
Out[92]:
45 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3x4x5
Float64Float64Float64Float64Float64
10.06015130.8276270.3346880.6677840.3483
20.6133620.7127440.756530.5701680.725836
30.3148610.1891660.8389130.04730690.543913
40.417240.3984430.9169890.9297370.559125
In [93]:
x[:, Between(:x2, :x4)]
Out[93]:
43 DataFrame
Rowx2x3x4
Float64Float64Float64
10.8276270.3346880.667784
20.7127440.756530.570168
30.1891660.8389130.0473069
40.3984430.9169890.929737
In [94]:
x[:, Cols("x1", Between("x2", "x4"))]
Out[94]:
44 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3x4
Float64Float64Float64Float64
10.06015130.8276270.3346880.667784
20.6133620.7127440.756530.570168
30.3148610.1891660.8389130.0473069
40.417240.3984430.9169890.929737

Views¶

You can simply create a view of a DataFrame (it is more efficient than creating a materialized selection). Here are the possible return value options.

In [95]:
@view x[1:2, 1]
Out[95]:
2-element view(::Vector{Float64}, 1:2) with eltype Float64:
 0.060151310846850214
 0.613361790955923
In [96]:
@view x[1,1]
Out[96]:
0-dimensional view(::Vector{Float64}, 1) with eltype Float64:
0.060151310846850214
In [97]:
@view x[1, 1:2] # a DataFrameRow, the same as for x[1, 1:2] without a view
Out[97]:
DataFrameRow (2 columns)
Rowx1x2
Float64Float64
10.06015130.827627
In [98]:
@view x[1:2, 1:2] # a SubDataFrame
Out[98]:
22 SubDataFrame
Rowx1x2
Float64Float64
10.06015130.827627
20.6133620.712744

Adding new columns to a data frame¶

In [99]:
df = DataFrame()
Out[99]:
00 DataFrame

using setproperty!

In [100]:
x = [1, 2, 3]
df.a = x
df
Out[100]:
31 DataFrame
Rowa
Int64
11
22
33
In [101]:
df.a === x 
# no copy is performed
Out[101]:
true

using setindex!

In [102]:
df[!, :b] = x
df[:, :c] = x
df
Out[102]:
33 DataFrame
Rowabc
Int64Int64Int64
1111
2222
3333
In [103]:
df.b === x 
# no copy
Out[103]:
true
In [104]:
df.c === x 
# copy
Out[104]:
false
In [105]:
df[!, :d] .= x
df[:, :e] .= x
df
Out[105]:
35 DataFrame
Rowabcde
Int64Int64Int64Int64Int64
111111
222222
333333
In [106]:
df.d === x, df.e === x 
# both copy, so in this case `!` and `:` has the same effect
Out[106]:
(false, false)

note that in our data frame columns :a and :b store the vector x (not a copy)

In [107]:
df.a === df.b === x
Out[107]:
true

DataFrames.jl supports a complete set of getindex, getproperty, setindex!, setproperty!, view, broadcasting, and broadcasting assignment operations. The details are explained here: http://juliadata.github.io/DataFrames.jl/latest/lib/indexing/.

Comparisons¶

In [108]:
df = DataFrame(rand(2,3), :auto)
Out[108]:
23 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3
Float64Float64Float64
10.9926690.6368170.463786
20.3926530.4178770.026269
In [109]:
df2 = copy(df)
Out[109]:
23 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3
Float64Float64Float64
10.9926690.6368170.463786
20.3926530.4178770.026269
In [110]:
df == df2 
# compares column names and contents
Out[110]:
true

create a minimally different data frame and use isapprox for comparison

In [111]:
df3 = df2 .+ eps()
Out[111]:
23 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3
Float64Float64Float64
10.9926690.6368170.463786
20.3926530.4178770.026269
In [112]:
df == df3
Out[112]:
false
In [113]:
isapprox(df, df3)
Out[113]:
true
In [114]:
isapprox(df, df3, atol = eps()/2)
Out[114]:
false

missings are handled as in Julia Base

In [115]:
df = DataFrame(a=missing)
Out[115]:
11 DataFrame
Rowa
Missing
1missing
In [116]:
df == df
Out[116]:
missing
In [117]:
df === df
Out[117]:
true
In [118]:
isequal(df, df)
Out[118]:
true

Metadata support¶

You can attach and retrieve metadata on table-level and column-level of a data frame as key-value pairs.

The most important functions you can use are:

  • metadata: get table-level metadata
  • metadata!: set table-level metadata
  • colmetadata: set table-level metadata
  • colmetadata!: set table-level metadata

Additionally each metadata key-value pair has a style information attached to it. In DataFrames.jl the metadata style influences how metadata is propagated when df is transformed. In general currently two styles are supported:

  • :default - no propagation under transformations
  • :note - metadata is preserved under transformations

Here is their example usage

In [119]:
df = DataFrame(date=[2011, 2012, 2013], sales=[12, 14, 13])
Out[119]:
32 DataFrame
Rowdatesales
Int64Int64
1201112
2201214
3201313
In [120]:
metadata!(df, "title", "Sales data for company ABC", style=:note)
colmetadata!(df, :date, "label", "Fiscal year", style=:note)
colmetadata!(df, :sales, "label", "Sales in units", style=:note)
Out[120]:
32 DataFrame
Rowdatesales
Int64Int64
1201112
2201214
3201313
In [121]:
show(stdout, MIME("text/html"), df, header=colmetadata.(Ref(df), 1:ncol(df), "label"), top_left_str=metadata(df, "title"))
Sales data for company ABC
RowFiscal yearSales in units
1201112
2201214
3201313

Metadata is especially useful if you:

  • work with multiple data frames that have many columns and it is hard to keep mental track of their interpretation, or
  • want to have an automated pipeline (e.g. for producing tables or figures) where custom annotations should be used (as in the examples above)

For more details please refer to https://dataframes.juliadata.org/stable/lib/metadata/ and TableMetadataTools.jl package.

Handling missing values¶

A singelton type Missing allows us to deal with missing values.

In [122]:
missing, typeof(missing)
Out[122]:
(missing, Missing)

Arrays automatically create an appropriate union type.

In [123]:
x = [1, 2, missing, 3]
Out[123]:
4-element Vector{Union{Missing, Int64}}:
 1
 2
  missing
 3

ismissing checks if passed value is missing.

In [124]:
ismissing(1), ismissing(missing), ismissing(x), ismissing.(x)
Out[124]:
(false, true, false, Bool[0, 0, 1, 0])

We can extract the type combined with Missing from a Union via nonmissingtype

(This is useful for arrays!)

In [125]:
eltype(x), nonmissingtype(eltype(x))
Out[125]:
(Union{Missing, Int64}, Int64)

missing comparisons produce missing.

In [126]:
missing == missing, missing != missing, missing < missing
Out[126]:
(missing, missing, missing)

This is also true when missings are compared with values of other types.

In [127]:
1 == missing, 1 != missing, 1 < missing
Out[127]:
(missing, missing, missing)

isequal, isless, and === produce results of type Bool. Notice that missing is considered greater than any numeric value.

In [128]:
isequal(missing, missing), missing === missing, isequal(1, missing), isless(1, missing)
Out[128]:
(true, true, false, true)

In the next few examples, we see that many (not all) functions handle missing.

In [129]:
map(x -> x(missing), [sin, cos, zero, sqrt]) # part 1
Out[129]:
4-element Vector{Missing}:
 missing
 missing
 missing
 missing
In [130]:
map(x -> x(missing, 1), [+, - , *, /, div]) # part 2
Out[130]:
5-element Vector{Missing}:
 missing
 missing
 missing
 missing
 missing
In [131]:
using Statistics # needed for mean
map(x -> x([1,2,missing]), [minimum, maximum, extrema, mean, float]) # part 3
Out[131]:
5-element Vector{Any}:
 missing
 missing
 (missing, missing)
 missing
 Union{Missing, Float64}[1.0, 2.0, missing]

skipmissing returns iterator skipping missing values. We can use collect and skipmissing to create an array that excludes these missing values.

In [132]:
collect(skipmissing([1, missing, 2, missing]))
Out[132]:
2-element Vector{Int64}:
 1
 2

Here we use replace to create a new array that replaces all missing values with some value (NaN in this case).

In [133]:
replace([1.0, missing, 2.0, missing], missing=>NaN)
Out[133]:
4-element Vector{Float64}:
   1.0
 NaN
   2.0
 NaN

Another way to do this:

In [134]:
coalesce.([1.0, missing, 2.0, missing], NaN)
Out[134]:
4-element Vector{Float64}:
   1.0
 NaN
   2.0
 NaN

You can also use recode from CategoricalArrays.jl if you have a default output value.

In [135]:
using CategoricalArrays
In [136]:
recode([1.0, missing, 2.0, missing], false, missing=>true)
Out[136]:
4-element Vector{Bool}:
 0
 1
 0
 1

There are also replace! and recode! functions that work in place.

Here is an example how you can to missing inputation in a data frame.

In [137]:
df = DataFrame(a=[1,2,missing], b=["a", "b", missing])
Out[137]:
32 DataFrame
Rowab
Int64?String?
11a
22b
3missingmissing

we change df.a vector in place.

In [138]:
replace!(df.a, missing=>100)
Out[138]:
3-element Vector{Union{Missing, Int64}}:
   1
   2
 100

Now we overwrite df.b with a new vector, because the replacement type is different than what eltype(df.b) accepts.

In [139]:
df.b = coalesce.(df.b, 100)
Out[139]:
3-element Vector{Any}:
    "a"
    "b"
 100
In [140]:
df
Out[140]:
32 DataFrame
Rowab
Int64?Any
11a
22b
3100100

You can use unique or levels to get unique values with or without missings, respectively.

In [141]:
unique([1, missing, 2, missing]), levels([1, missing, 2, missing])
Out[141]:
(Union{Missing, Int64}[1, missing, 2], [1, 2])

In this next example, we convert x to y with allowmissing, where y has a type that accepts missings.

In [142]:
x = [1,2,3]
y = allowmissing(x)
Out[142]:
3-element Vector{Union{Missing, Int64}}:
 1
 2
 3

Then, we convert back with disallowmissing. This would fail if y contained missing values!

In [143]:
z = disallowmissing(y)
x,y,z
Out[143]:
([1, 2, 3], Union{Missing, Int64}[1, 2, 3], [1, 2, 3])

disallowmissing has error keyword argument that can be used to decide how it should behave when it encounters a column that actually contains a missing value

In [144]:
df = allowmissing(DataFrame(ones(2,3), :auto))
Out[144]:
23 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3
Float64?Float64?Float64?
11.01.01.0
21.01.01.0
In [145]:
df[1,1] = missing
Out[145]:
missing
In [146]:
df
Out[146]:
23 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3
Float64?Float64?Float64?
1missing1.01.0
21.01.01.0
In [147]:
disallowmissing(df) # an error is thrown

ArgumentError: Missing value found in column :x1 in row 1

Stacktrace:
 [1] disallowmissing(df::DataFrame, cols::Colon; error::Bool)
   @ DataFrames C:\Users\user\.julia\packages\DataFrames\58MUJ\src\abstractdataframe\abstractdataframe.jl:2229
 [2] disallowmissing (repeats 2 times)
   @ C:\Users\user\.julia\packages\DataFrames\58MUJ\src\abstractdataframe\abstractdataframe.jl:2215 [inlined]
 [3] top-level scope
   @ In[147]:1
In [148]:
disallowmissing(df, error=false) # column :x1 is left untouched as it contains missing
Out[148]:
23 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3
Float64?Float64Float64
1missing1.01.0
21.01.01.0

In this next example, we show that the type of each column in x is initially Int64. After using allowmissing! to accept missing values in columns 1 and 3, the types of those columns become Union{Int64,Missing}.

In [149]:
x = DataFrame(rand(Int, 2,3), :auto)
println("Before: ", eltype.(eachcol(x)))
allowmissing!(x, 1) # make first column accept missings
allowmissing!(x, :x3) # make :x3 column accept missings
println("After: ", eltype.(eachcol(x)))

Before: DataType[Int64, Int64, Int64]
After: Type[Union{Missing, Int64}, Int64, Union{Missing, Int64}]

In this next example, we'll use completecases to find all the rows of a DataFrame that have complete data.

In [150]:
x = DataFrame(A=[1, missing, 3, 4], B=["A", "B", missing, "C"])
Out[150]:
42 DataFrame
RowAB
Int64?String?
11A
2missingB
33missing
44C
In [151]:
println("Complete cases:\n", completecases(x))

Complete cases:
Bool[1, 0, 0, 1]

We can use dropmissing or dropmissing! to remove the rows with incomplete data from a DataFrame and either create a new DataFrame or mutate the original in-place.

In [152]:
y = dropmissing(x)
dropmissing!(x)
Out[152]:
22 DataFrame
RowAB
Int64String
11A
24C
In [153]:
x
Out[153]:
22 DataFrame
RowAB
Int64String
11A
24C
In [154]:
y
Out[154]:
22 DataFrame
RowAB
Int64String
11A
24C

When we call describe on a DataFrame with dropped missing values, the columns do not allow missing values any more by default.

In [155]:
describe(x)
Out[155]:
27 DataFrame
Rowvariablemeanminmedianmaxnmissingeltype
SymbolUnionAnyUnionAnyInt64DataType
1A2.512.540Int64
2BAC0String

Alternatively you can pass disallowmissing keyword argument to dropmissing and dropmissing!

In [156]:
x = DataFrame(A=[1, missing, 3, 4], B=["A", "B", missing, "C"])
Out[156]:
42 DataFrame
RowAB
Int64?String?
11A
2missingB
33missing
44C
In [157]:
dropmissing!(x, disallowmissing=false)
Out[157]:
22 DataFrame
RowAB
Int64?String?
11A
24C

Making functions missing-aware¶

If we have a function that does not handle missing values we can wrap it using passmissing function so that if any of its positional arguments is missing we will get a missing value in return. In the example below we change how string function behaves:

In [158]:
string(missing)
Out[158]:
"missing"
In [159]:
string(missing, " ", missing)
Out[159]:
"missing missing"
In [160]:
string(1,2,3)
Out[160]:
"123"
In [161]:
lift_string = passmissing(string)
Out[161]:
(::Missings.PassMissing{typeof(string)}) (generic function with 2 methods)
In [162]:
lift_string(missing)
Out[162]:
missing
In [163]:
lift_string(missing, " ", missing)
Out[163]:
missing
In [164]:
lift_string(1, 2, 3)
Out[164]:
"123"

Aggregating rows containing missing values¶

Create an example data frame containing missing values:

In [165]:
df = DataFrame(a = [1, missing, missing], b=[1, 2, missing])
Out[165]:
32 DataFrame
Rowab
Int64?Int64?
111
2missing2
3missingmissing

If we just run sum on the rows we get two missing entries:

In [166]:
sum.(eachrow(df))
Out[166]:
3-element Vector{Union{Missing, Int64}}:
 2
  missing
  missing

One can apply skipmissing on the rows to avoid this problem:

In [167]:
sum.(skipmissing.(eachrow(df)))

ArgumentError: reducing over an empty collection is not allowed

However, we get an error. The problem is that the last row of df contains only missing values, and since eachrow is type unstable the eltype of the result of skipmissing is unknown (so it is marked Any)

In [168]:
collect(skipmissing(eachrow(df)[end]))
Out[168]:
Any[]

In such cases it is useful to switch to Tables.namedtupleiterator which is type stable as discussed in 01_constructors.ipynb notebook.

In [169]:
sum.(skipmissing.(Tables.namedtupleiterator(df)))
Out[169]:
3-element Vector{Int64}:
 2
 2
 0

Later in the tutorial you will learn that you can efficiently calculate such sums using the select function:

In [170]:
select(df, AsTable(:) => ByRow(sumskipmissing))
Out[170]:
31 DataFrame
Rowa_b_sum_skipmissing
Int64
12
22
30

Note that it correctly handles the rows with all missing values.

Load and save DataFrames¶

We do not cover all features of the packages. Please refer to their documentation to learn them.

Here we'll load CSV.jl to read and write CSV files and Arrow.jl, JLSO.jl, and serialization, which allow us to work with a binary format and JSONTables.jl for JSON interaction. Finally we consider a custom JDF.jl format.

In [171]:
using CSV

Let's create a simple DataFrame for testing purposes,

In [172]:
x = DataFrame(A=[true, false, true], B=[1, 2, missing],
              C=[missing, "b", "c"], D=['a', missing, 'c'])
Out[172]:
34 DataFrame
RowABCD
BoolInt64?String?Char?
1true1missinga
2false2bmissing
3truemissingcc

and use eltypes to look at the columnwise types.

In [173]:
eltype.(eachcol(x))
Out[173]:
4-element Vector{Type}:
 Bool
 Union{Missing, Int64}
 Union{Missing, String}
 Union{Missing, Char}

CSV.jl¶

Let's use CSV to save x to disk; make sure x1.csv does not conflict with some file in your working directory.

In [174]:
CSV.write("x1.csv", x)
Out[174]:
"x1.csv"

Now we can see how it was saved by reading x.csv.

In [175]:
print(read("x1.csv", String))

A,B,C,D
true,1,,a
false,2,b,
true,,c,c

We can also load it back.

In [176]:
y = CSV.read("x1.csv", DataFrame)
Out[176]:
34 DataFrame
RowABCD
BoolInt64?String1?String1?
1true1missinga
2false2bmissing
3truemissingcc

Note that when loading in a DataFrame from a CSV the column type for columns :C :D have changed to use special strings defined in the InlineStrings.jl package.

In [177]:
eltype.(eachcol(y))
Out[177]:
4-element Vector{Type}:
 Bool
 Union{Missing, Int64}
 Union{Missing, String1}
 Union{Missing, String1}

We first generate a random data frame

Manipulating columns of a DataFrame¶

Renaming columns¶

Let's start with a DataFrame of Bools that has default column names.

In [179]:
x = DataFrame(rand(Bool, 3, 4), :auto)
Out[179]:
34 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3x4
BoolBoolBoolBool
1truetruefalsetrue
2truefalsefalsefalse
3truefalsetruetrue

With rename, we create new DataFrame; here we rename the column :x1 to :A. (rename also accepts collections of Pairs.)

In [180]:
rename(x, :x1 => :A)
Out[180]:
34 DataFrame
RowAx2x3x4
BoolBoolBoolBool
1truetruefalsetrue
2truefalsefalsefalse
3truefalsetruetrue

With rename! we do an in place transformation.

This time we've applied a function to every column name (note that the function gets a column names as a string).

In [181]:
rename!(c -> c^2, x)
Out[181]:
34 DataFrame
Rowx1x1x2x2x3x3x4x4
BoolBoolBoolBool
1truetruefalsetrue
2truefalsefalsefalse
3truefalsetruetrue

We can also change the name of a particular column without knowing the original.

Here we change the name of the third column, creating a new DataFrame.

In [182]:
rename(x, 3 => :third)
Out[182]:
34 DataFrame
Rowx1x1x2x2thirdx4x4
BoolBoolBoolBool
1truetruefalsetrue
2truefalsefalsefalse
3truefalsetruetrue

If we pass a vector of names to rename!, we can change the names of all variables.

In [183]:
rename!(x, [:a, :b, :c, :d])
Out[183]:
34 DataFrame
Rowabcd
BoolBoolBoolBool
1truetruefalsetrue
2truefalsefalsefalse
3truefalsetruetrue

In all the above examples you could have used strings instead of symbols, e.g.

In [184]:
rename!(x, string.('a':'d'))
Out[184]:
34 DataFrame
Rowabcd
BoolBoolBoolBool
1truetruefalsetrue
2truefalsefalsefalse
3truefalsetruetrue

rename! allows for circular renaming of columns, e.g.:

In [185]:
x
Out[185]:
34 DataFrame
Rowabcd
BoolBoolBoolBool
1truetruefalsetrue
2truefalsefalsefalse
3truefalsetruetrue
In [186]:
rename!(x, "a"=>"d", "d"=>"a")
Out[186]:
34 DataFrame
Rowdbca
BoolBoolBoolBool
1truetruefalsetrue
2truefalsefalsefalse
3truefalsetruetrue

We get an error when we try to provide duplicate names

In [187]:
rename(x, fill(:a, 4))

ArgumentError: Duplicate variable names: :a. Pass makeunique=true to make them unique using a suffix automatically.

Stacktrace:
 [1] rename!(x::DataFrames.Index, nms::Vector{Symbol}; makeunique::Bool)
   @ DataFrames C:\Users\user\.julia\packages\DataFrames\58MUJ\src\other\index.jl:51
 [2] #rename!#57
   @ C:\Users\user\.julia\packages\DataFrames\58MUJ\src\abstractdataframe\abstractdataframe.jl:201 [inlined]
 [3] #rename#63
   @ C:\Users\user\.julia\packages\DataFrames\58MUJ\src\abstractdataframe\abstractdataframe.jl:356 [inlined]
 [4] rename(df::DataFrame, vals::Vector{Symbol})
   @ DataFrames C:\Users\user\.julia\packages\DataFrames\58MUJ\src\abstractdataframe\abstractdataframe.jl:356
 [5] top-level scope
   @ In[187]:1

unless we pass makeunique=true, which allows us to handle duplicates in passed names.

In [188]:
rename(x, fill(:a, 4), makeunique=true)
Out[188]:
34 DataFrame
Rowaa_1a_2a_3
BoolBoolBoolBool
1truetruefalsetrue
2truefalsefalsefalse
3truefalsetruetrue

Reordering columns¶

We can reorder the names(x) vector as needed, creating a new DataFrame.

In [189]:
using Random
Random.seed!(1234)
x[:, shuffle(names(x))]
Out[189]:
34 DataFrame
Rowdbca
BoolBoolBoolBool
1truetruefalsetrue
2truefalsefalsefalse
3truefalsetruetrue

Also select! can be used to achieve this in place (or select to perform a copy):

In [190]:
x
Out[190]:
34 DataFrame
Rowdbca
BoolBoolBoolBool
1truetruefalsetrue
2truefalsefalsefalse
3truefalsetruetrue
In [191]:
select!(x, 4:-1:1);
x
Out[191]:
34 DataFrame
Rowacbd
BoolBoolBoolBool
1truefalsetruetrue
2falsefalsefalsetrue
3truetruefalsetrue

Merging/adding columns¶

In [192]:
x = DataFrame([(i,j) for i in 1:3, j in 1:4], :auto)
Out[192]:
34 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3x4
TupleTupleTupleTuple
1(1, 1)(1, 2)(1, 3)(1, 4)
2(2, 1)(2, 2)(2, 3)(2, 4)
3(3, 1)(3, 2)(3, 3)(3, 4)

With hcat we can merge two DataFrames. Also [x y] syntax is supported but only when DataFrames have unique column names.

In [193]:
hcat(x, x, makeunique=true)
Out[193]:
38 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3x4x1_1x2_1x3_1x4_1
TupleTupleTupleTupleTupleTupleTupleTuple
1(1, 1)(1, 2)(1, 3)(1, 4)(1, 1)(1, 2)(1, 3)(1, 4)
2(2, 1)(2, 2)(2, 3)(2, 4)(2, 1)(2, 2)(2, 3)(2, 4)
3(3, 1)(3, 2)(3, 3)(3, 4)(3, 1)(3, 2)(3, 3)(3, 4)

You can append a vector to a data frame with the following syntax:

In [194]:
y = [x DataFrame(A=[1, 2, 3])]
Out[194]:
35 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3x4A
TupleTupleTupleTupleInt64
1(1, 1)(1, 2)(1, 3)(1, 4)1
2(2, 1)(2, 2)(2, 3)(2, 4)2
3(3, 1)(3, 2)(3, 3)(3, 4)3

Here we do the same but add column :A to the front.

In [195]:
y = [DataFrame(A=[1, 2, 3]) x]
Out[195]:
35 DataFrame
RowAx1x2x3x4
Int64TupleTupleTupleTuple
11(1, 1)(1, 2)(1, 3)(1, 4)
22(2, 1)(2, 2)(2, 3)(2, 4)
33(3, 1)(3, 2)(3, 3)(3, 4)

A column can also be added in the middle. Here a brute-force method is used and a new DataFrame is created.

In [196]:
using BenchmarkTools
@btime [$x[!, 1:2] DataFrame(A=[1,2,3]) $x[!, 3:4]]

  4.767 s (81 allocations: 6.59 KiB)
Out[196]:
35 DataFrame
Rowx1x2Ax3x4
TupleTupleInt64TupleTuple
1(1, 1)(1, 2)1(1, 3)(1, 4)
2(2, 1)(2, 2)2(2, 3)(2, 4)
3(3, 1)(3, 2)3(3, 3)(3, 4)

We could also do this with a specialized in place method insertcols!. Let's add :newcol to the DataFrame y.

In [197]:
insertcols!(y, 2, "newcol" => [1,2,3])
Out[197]:
36 DataFrame
RowAnewcolx1x2x3x4
Int64Int64TupleTupleTupleTuple
111(1, 1)(1, 2)(1, 3)(1, 4)
222(2, 1)(2, 2)(2, 3)(2, 4)
333(3, 1)(3, 2)(3, 3)(3, 4)

If you want to insert the same column name several times makeunique=true is needed as usual.

In [198]:
insertcols!(y, 2, :newcol => [1,2,3], makeunique=true)
Out[198]:
37 DataFrame
RowAnewcol_1newcolx1x2x3x4
Int64Int64Int64TupleTupleTupleTuple
1111(1, 1)(1, 2)(1, 3)(1, 4)
2222(2, 1)(2, 2)(2, 3)(2, 4)
3333(3, 1)(3, 2)(3, 3)(3, 4)

We can see how much faster it is to insert a column with insertcols! than with hcat using @btime (note that we use here a Pair notation as an example).

In [199]:
@btime insertcols!(copy($x), 3, :A => [1,2,3])

  1.580 s (21 allocations: 1.91 KiB)
Out[199]:
35 DataFrame
Rowx1x2Ax3x4
TupleTupleInt64TupleTuple
1(1, 1)(1, 2)1(1, 3)(1, 4)
2(2, 1)(2, 2)2(2, 3)(2, 4)
3(3, 1)(3, 2)3(3, 3)(3, 4)

Let's use insertcols! to append a column in place (note that we dropped the index at which we insert the column)

In [200]:
insertcols!(x, :A => [1,2,3])
Out[200]:
35 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3x4A
TupleTupleTupleTupleInt64
1(1, 1)(1, 2)(1, 3)(1, 4)1
2(2, 1)(2, 2)(2, 3)(2, 4)2
3(3, 1)(3, 2)(3, 3)(3, 4)3

and to in place prepend a column.

In [201]:
insertcols!(x, 1, :B => [1,2,3])
Out[201]:
36 DataFrame
RowBx1x2x3x4A
Int64TupleTupleTupleTupleInt64
11(1, 1)(1, 2)(1, 3)(1, 4)1
22(2, 1)(2, 2)(2, 3)(2, 4)2
33(3, 1)(3, 2)(3, 3)(3, 4)3

Note that insertcols! can be used to insert several columns to a data frame at once and that it performs broadcasting if needed:

In [202]:
df = DataFrame(a = [1, 2, 3])
Out[202]:
31 DataFrame
Rowa
Int64
11
22
33
In [203]:
insertcols!(df, :b => "x", :c => 'a':'c', :d => Ref([1,2,3]))
Out[203]:
34 DataFrame
Rowabcd
Int64StringCharArray
11xa[1, 2, 3]
22xb[1, 2, 3]
33xc[1, 2, 3]

Interestingly we can emulate hcat mutating the data frame in-place using insertcols!:

In [204]:
df1 = DataFrame(a=[1,2])
Out[204]:
21 DataFrame
Rowa
Int64
11
22
In [205]:
df2 = DataFrame(b=[2,3], c=[3,4])
Out[205]:
22 DataFrame
Rowbc
Int64Int64
123
234
In [206]:
hcat(df1, df2)
Out[206]:
23 DataFrame
Rowabc
Int64Int64Int64
1123
2234
In [207]:
df1 
# df1 is not touched
Out[207]:
21 DataFrame
Rowa
Int64
11
22
In [208]:
insertcols!(df1, pairs(eachcol(df2))...)
Out[208]:
23 DataFrame
Rowabc
Int64Int64Int64
1123
2234
In [209]:
df1 
# now we have changed df1
Out[209]:
23 DataFrame
Rowabc
Int64Int64Int64
1123
2234

Subsetting/removing columns¶

Let's create a new DataFrame x and show a few ways to create DataFrames with a subset of x's columns.

In [210]:
x = DataFrame([(i,j) for i in 1:3, j in 1:5], :auto)
Out[210]:
35 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3x4x5
TupleTupleTupleTupleTuple
1(1, 1)(1, 2)(1, 3)(1, 4)(1, 5)
2(2, 1)(2, 2)(2, 3)(2, 4)(2, 5)
3(3, 1)(3, 2)(3, 3)(3, 4)(3, 5)

First we could do this by index:

In [211]:
x[:, [1,2,4,5]] # use ! instead of : for non-copying operation
Out[211]:
34 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x4x5
TupleTupleTupleTuple
1(1, 1)(1, 2)(1, 4)(1, 5)
2(2, 1)(2, 2)(2, 4)(2, 5)
3(3, 1)(3, 2)(3, 4)(3, 5)

or by column name:

In [212]:
x[:, [:x1, :x4]]
Out[212]:
32 DataFrame
Rowx1x4
TupleTuple
1(1, 1)(1, 4)
2(2, 1)(2, 4)
3(3, 1)(3, 4)

We can also choose to keep or exclude columns by Bool (we need a vector whose length is the number of columns in the original DataFrame).

In [213]:
x[:, [true, false, true, false, true]]
Out[213]:
33 DataFrame
Rowx1x3x5
TupleTupleTuple
1(1, 1)(1, 3)(1, 5)
2(2, 1)(2, 3)(2, 5)
3(3, 1)(3, 3)(3, 5)

Here we create a single column DataFrame,

In [214]:
x[:, [:x1]]
Out[214]:
31 DataFrame
Rowx1
Tuple
1(1, 1)
2(2, 1)
3(3, 1)

and here we access the vector contained in column :x1.

In [215]:
x[!, :x1] # use : instead of ! to copy
Out[215]:
3-element Vector{Tuple{Int64, Int64}}:
 (1, 1)
 (2, 1)
 (3, 1)
In [216]:
x.x1 # the same
Out[216]:
3-element Vector{Tuple{Int64, Int64}}:
 (1, 1)
 (2, 1)
 (3, 1)

We could grab the same vector by column number

In [217]:
x[!, 1]
Out[217]:
3-element Vector{Tuple{Int64, Int64}}:
 (1, 1)
 (2, 1)
 (3, 1)

Note that getting a single column returns it without copying while creating a new DataFrame performs a copy of the column

In [218]:
x[!, 1] === x[!, [1]]
Out[218]:
false

you can also use Regex, Cols, All, Between and Not from InvertedIndies.jl for column selection:

In [219]:
x[!, r"[12]"]
Out[219]:
32 DataFrame
Rowx1x2
TupleTuple
1(1, 1)(1, 2)
2(2, 1)(2, 2)
3(3, 1)(3, 2)
In [220]:
x[!, Not(1)]
Out[220]:
34 DataFrame
Rowx2x3x4x5
TupleTupleTupleTuple
1(1, 2)(1, 3)(1, 4)(1, 5)
2(2, 2)(2, 3)(2, 4)(2, 5)
3(3, 2)(3, 3)(3, 4)(3, 5)
In [221]:
x[!, Between(:x2, :x4)]
Out[221]:
33 DataFrame
Rowx2x3x4
TupleTupleTuple
1(1, 2)(1, 3)(1, 4)
2(2, 2)(2, 3)(2, 4)
3(3, 2)(3, 3)(3, 4)
In [222]:
x[!, Cols(:x1, Between(:x3, :x5))]
Out[222]:
34 DataFrame
Rowx1x3x4x5
TupleTupleTupleTuple
1(1, 1)(1, 3)(1, 4)(1, 5)
2(2, 1)(2, 3)(2, 4)(2, 5)
3(3, 1)(3, 3)(3, 4)(3, 5)
In [223]:
x[!, Cols(Between(:x3, :x5), :x4, operator=setdiff)]
Out[223]:
32 DataFrame
Rowx3x5
TupleTuple
1(1, 3)(1, 5)
2(2, 3)(2, 5)
3(3, 3)(3, 5)
In [224]:
select(x, :x1, Between(:x3, :x5), copycols=false)
Out[224]:
34 DataFrame
Rowx1x3x4x5
TupleTupleTupleTuple
1(1, 1)(1, 3)(1, 4)(1, 5)
2(2, 1)(2, 3)(2, 4)(2, 5)
3(3, 1)(3, 3)(3, 4)(3, 5)

you can use select and select! functions to select a subset of columns from a data frame. select creates a new data frame and select! operates in place

In [225]:
df = copy(x)
Out[225]:
35 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3x4x5
TupleTupleTupleTupleTuple
1(1, 1)(1, 2)(1, 3)(1, 4)(1, 5)
2(2, 1)(2, 2)(2, 3)(2, 4)(2, 5)
3(3, 1)(3, 2)(3, 3)(3, 4)(3, 5)
In [226]:
df2 = select(df, [1, 2])
Out[226]:
32 DataFrame
Rowx1x2
TupleTuple
1(1, 1)(1, 2)
2(2, 1)(2, 2)
3(3, 1)(3, 2)
In [227]:
select(df, Not([1, 2]))
Out[227]:
33 DataFrame
Rowx3x4x5
TupleTupleTuple
1(1, 3)(1, 4)(1, 5)
2(2, 3)(2, 4)(2, 5)
3(3, 3)(3, 4)(3, 5)

by default select copies columns

In [228]:
df2[!, 1] === df[!, 1]
Out[228]:
false

this can be avoided by using copycols=false keyword argument

In [229]:
df2 = select(df, [1, 2], copycols=false)
Out[229]:
32 DataFrame
Rowx1x2
TupleTuple
1(1, 1)(1, 2)
2(2, 1)(2, 2)
3(3, 1)(3, 2)
In [230]:
df2[!, 1] === df[!, 1]
Out[230]:
true

using select! will modify the source data frame

In [231]:
select!(df, [1,2])
Out[231]:
32 DataFrame
Rowx1x2
TupleTuple
1(1, 1)(1, 2)
2(2, 1)(2, 2)
3(3, 1)(3, 2)
In [232]:
df == df2
Out[232]:
true

Here we create a copy of x and delete the 3rd column from the copy with select! and Not.

In [233]:
z = copy(x)
select!(z, Not(3))
Out[233]:
34 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x4x5
TupleTupleTupleTuple
1(1, 1)(1, 2)(1, 4)(1, 5)
2(2, 1)(2, 2)(2, 4)(2, 5)
3(3, 1)(3, 2)(3, 4)(3, 5)

alternatively we can achieve the same by using the select function

In [234]:
select(x, Not(3))
Out[234]:
34 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x4x5
TupleTupleTupleTuple
1(1, 1)(1, 2)(1, 4)(1, 5)
2(2, 1)(2, 2)(2, 4)(2, 5)
3(3, 1)(3, 2)(3, 4)(3, 5)

x stays unchanged

In [235]:
x
Out[235]:
35 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3x4x5
TupleTupleTupleTupleTuple
1(1, 1)(1, 2)(1, 3)(1, 4)(1, 5)
2(2, 1)(2, 2)(2, 3)(2, 4)(2, 5)
3(3, 1)(3, 2)(3, 3)(3, 4)(3, 5)

Views¶

Note, that you can also create a view of a DataFrame when we want a subset of its columns:

In [236]:
@btime x[:, [1,3,5]]

  1.510 s (23 allocations: 2.09 KiB)
Out[236]:
33 DataFrame
Rowx1x3x5
TupleTupleTuple
1(1, 1)(1, 3)(1, 5)
2(2, 1)(2, 3)(2, 5)
3(3, 1)(3, 3)(3, 5)
In [237]:
@btime @view x[:, [1,3,5]]

  312.971 ns (5 allocations: 320 bytes)
Out[237]:
33 SubDataFrame
Rowx1x3x5
TupleTupleTuple
1(1, 1)(1, 3)(1, 5)
2(2, 1)(2, 3)(2, 5)
3(3, 1)(3, 3)(3, 5)

(now creation of the view is slow, but in the coming releases of the DataFrames.jl package it will become significantly faster)

Modify column by name¶

In [238]:
x = DataFrame([(i,j) for i in 1:3, j in 1:5], :auto)
Out[238]:
35 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3x4x5
TupleTupleTupleTupleTuple
1(1, 1)(1, 2)(1, 3)(1, 4)(1, 5)
2(2, 1)(2, 2)(2, 3)(2, 4)(2, 5)
3(3, 1)(3, 2)(3, 3)(3, 4)(3, 5)

With the following syntax, the existing column is modified without performing any copying (this is discouraged as it creates column alias).

In [239]:
x[!, :x1] = x[!, :x2]
x
Out[239]:
35 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3x4x5
TupleTupleTupleTupleTuple
1(1, 2)(1, 2)(1, 3)(1, 4)(1, 5)
2(2, 2)(2, 2)(2, 3)(2, 4)(2, 5)
3(3, 2)(3, 2)(3, 3)(3, 4)(3, 5)

this syntax is safer

In [240]:
x[!, :x1] = x[:, :x2]
Out[240]:
3-element Vector{Tuple{Int64, Int64}}:
 (1, 2)
 (2, 2)
 (3, 2)

We can also use the following syntax to add a new column at the end of a DataFrame.

In [241]:
x[!, :A] = [1,2,3]
x
Out[241]:
36 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3x4x5A
TupleTupleTupleTupleTupleInt64
1(1, 2)(1, 2)(1, 3)(1, 4)(1, 5)1
2(2, 2)(2, 2)(2, 3)(2, 4)(2, 5)2
3(3, 2)(3, 2)(3, 3)(3, 4)(3, 5)3

A new column name will be added to our DataFrame with the following syntax as well:

In [242]:
x.B = 11:13
x
Out[242]:
37 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3x4x5AB
TupleTupleTupleTupleTupleInt64Int64
1(1, 2)(1, 2)(1, 3)(1, 4)(1, 5)111
2(2, 2)(2, 2)(2, 3)(2, 4)(2, 5)212
3(3, 2)(3, 2)(3, 3)(3, 4)(3, 5)313

Find column name¶

In [243]:
x = DataFrame([(i,j) for i in 1:3, j in 1:5], :auto)
Out[243]:
35 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3x4x5
TupleTupleTupleTupleTuple
1(1, 1)(1, 2)(1, 3)(1, 4)(1, 5)
2(2, 1)(2, 2)(2, 3)(2, 4)(2, 5)
3(3, 1)(3, 2)(3, 3)(3, 4)(3, 5)

We can check if a column with a given name exists via

In [244]:
hasproperty(x, :x1)
Out[244]:
true

and determine its index via

In [245]:
columnindex(x, :x2)
Out[245]:
2

Advanced ways of column selection¶

these are most useful for non-standard column names (e.g. containing spaces)

In [246]:
df = DataFrame()
df.x1 = 1:3
df[!, "column 2"] = 4:6
df
Out[246]:
32 DataFrame
Rowx1column 2
Int64Int64
114
225
336
In [247]:
df."column 2"
Out[247]:
3-element Vector{Int64}:
 4
 5
 6
In [248]:
df[:, "column 2"]
Out[248]:
3-element Vector{Int64}:
 4
 5
 6

or you can interpolate column name using :() syntax

In [249]:
for n in names(df)
    println(n, "\n", df.:($n), "\n")
end

x1
[1, 2, 3]

column 2
[4, 5, 6]

Working on a collection of columns¶

When using eachcol of a data frame the resulting object retains reference to its parent and e.g. can be queried with getproperty

In [250]:
df = DataFrame(reshape(1:12, 3, 4), :auto)
Out[250]:
34 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3x4
Int64Int64Int64Int64
114710
225811
336912
In [251]:
ec_df = eachcol(df)
Out[251]:
34 DataFrameColumns
Rowx1x2x3x4
Int64Int64Int64Int64
114710
225811
336912
In [252]:
ec_df[1]
Out[252]:
3-element Vector{Int64}:
 1
 2
 3
In [253]:
ec_df.x1
Out[253]:
3-element Vector{Int64}:
 1
 2
 3

Transforming columns¶

We will get to this subject later in 10_transforms.ipynb notebook, but here let us just note that select, select!, transform, transform! and combine functions allow to generate new columns based on the old columns of a data frame.

The general rules are the following:

  • select and transform always return the number of rows equal to the source data frame, while combine returns any number of rows (combine is allowed to combine rows of the source data frame)
  • transform retains columns from the old data frame
  • select! and transform! are in-place versions of select and transform
In [254]:
df = DataFrame(reshape(1:12, 3, 4), :auto)
Out[254]:
34 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3x4
Int64Int64Int64Int64
114710
225811
336912

Here we add a new column :res that is a sum of columns :x1 and :x2. A general syntax of transformations of this kind is:

source_columns => function_to_apply => target_column_name

then function_to_apply gets columns selected by source_columns as positional arguments.

In [255]:
transform(df, [:x1, :x2] => (+) => :res)
Out[255]:
35 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3x4res
Int64Int64Int64Int64Int64
1147105
2258117
3369129

One can omit passing target_column_name in which case it is automatically generated:

In [256]:
# using Statistics
In [257]:
combine(df, [:x1, :x2] => cor)
Out[257]:
11 DataFrame
Rowx1_x2_cor
Float64
11.0

Note that combine allowed the number of columns in the resulting data frame to be changed. If we used select instead it would automatically broadcast the return value to match the number of rouws of the source:

In [258]:
select(df, [:x1, :x2] => cor)
Out[258]:
31 DataFrame
Rowx1_x2_cor
Float64
11.0
21.0
31.0

If you want to apply some function on each row of the source wrap it in ByRow:

In [259]:
select(df, :x1, :x2, [:x1, :x2] => ByRow(string))
Out[259]:
33 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x1_x2_string
Int64Int64String
11414
22525
33636

Also if you want columns to be passed as a NamedTuple to a funcion (instead of being positional arguments) wrap them in AsTable:

In [260]:
select(df, :x1, :x2, AsTable([:x1, :x2]) => x -> x.x1 + x.x2)
Out[260]:
33 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x1_x2_function
Int64Int64Int64
1145
2257
3369

For simplicity (as this functionality is often needed) there is a special treatement of nrow function that can be just passed as a transformation (without specifying of column selector):

In [261]:
select(df, :x1, nrow => "number_of_rows")
Out[261]:
32 DataFrame
Rowx1number_of_rows
Int64Int64
113
223
333

(note that in select the number of rows is automatically broadcasted to match the number of rows of the source data frame)

Finally you can conveninently create multiple columns with one function, e.g.:

In [262]:
select(df, :x1, :x1 => ByRow(x -> [x ^ 2, x ^ 3]) => ["x1", "x1"])
Out[262]:
33 DataFrame
Rowx1x1x1
Int64Int64Int64
1111
2248
33927

or e.g. (this produces the same result)

In [263]:
select(df, :x1, :x1 => (x -> DataFrame("x1" => x .^ 2, "x1" => x .^ 3)) => AsTable)
Out[263]:
33 DataFrame
Rowx1x1x1
Int64Int64Int64
1111
2248
33927

Note that since DataFrames.jl row aggregation for wide tables is efficient. Here is an example of a wide table with sum (other standard reductions are similarly supported):

large_df = DataFrame(rand(1000, 10000), :auto)

using : as row selector will copy columns

Also supported are pushfirst! and insert!.

Please consult the documentation of push!, append! and vcat (and related functions) for allowed values of cols keyword argument. This keyword argument governs the way these functions perform column matching of passed arguments. Also append! and push! support a promote keyword argument that decides if column type promotion is allowed.

Let us here just give a quick example of how heterogeneous data can be stored in the data frame using these functionalities:

In [310]:
source = [(a=1, b=2), (a=missing, b=10, c=20), (b="s", c=1, d=1)]
Out[310]:
3-element Vector{NamedTuple}:
 (a = 1, b = 2)
 (a = missing, b = 10, c = 20)
 (b = "s", c = 1, d = 1)
In [311]:
df = DataFrame()
Out[311]:
00 DataFrame
In [312]:
for row in source
    push!(df, row, cols=:union) # if cols is :union then promote is true by default
end
In [313]:
df
Out[313]:
34 DataFrame
Rowabcd
Int64?AnyInt64?Int64?
112missingmissing
2missing1020missing
3missings11

and we see that push! dynamically added columns as needed and updated their element types

In [330]:
filter!(x) do r
    if r.x1 > 2.5

    r.x3 < 3.5

A common operation is selection of rows for which a value in a column is contained in a given set. Here are a few ways in which you can achieve this.

In [331]:
df = DataFrame(x=1:12, y=mod1.(1:12, 4))
Out[331]:
122 DataFrame
Rowxy
Int64Int64
111
222

773

10102
11113
12124

We select rows for which column y has value 1 or 4.

In [332]:
filter(row -> row.y in [1,4], df)
Out[332]:
62 DataFrame
Rowxy
Int64Int64
111
244
351
484
591
6124
In [333]:
filter(:y => in([1,4]), df)
Out[333]:
62 DataFrame
Rowxy
Int64Int64
111
244
351
484
591
6124
In [334]:
df[in.(df.y, Ref([1,4])), :]
Out[334]:
62 DataFrame
Rowxy
Int64Int64
111
244
351
484
591
6124

DataFrames.jl also provides a subset function that works on whole columns and allows for multiple conditions:

In [335]:
x = DataFrame([1:4, 2:5, 3:6], :auto)
Out[335]:
43 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3
Int64Int64Int64
1123
2234
3345
4456
In [336]:
subset(x, :x1 => x -> x .< mean(x), :x2 => ByRow(<(2.5)))
Out[336]:
13 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3
Int64Int64Int64
1123

Similarly an in-place subset! function is provided.

Extracting one row from a DataFrame into standard collections¶

In [346]:
x = DataFrame(x=[1,missing,2], y=["a", "b", missing], z=[true,false,true])
Out[346]:
33 DataFrame
Rowxyz
Int64?String?Bool
11atrue
2missingbfalse
32missingtrue
In [347]:
cols = [:y, :z]
Out[347]:
2-element Vector{Symbol}:
 :y
 :z

you can use a conversion to a Vector or an Array

In [348]:
Vector(x[1, cols])
Out[348]:
2-element Vector{Any}:
     "a"
 true
In [349]:
Array(x[1, cols]) # the same
Out[349]:
2-element Vector{Any}:
     "a"
 true

now you will get a vector of vectors

In [350]:
[Vector(x[i, cols]) for i in axes(x, 1)]
Out[350]:
3-element Vector{Vector{Any}}:
 ["a", true]
 ["b", false]
 [missing, true]

it is easy to convert a DataFrameRow into a NamedTuple

In [351]:
copy(x[1, cols])
Out[351]:
NamedTuple{(:y, :z), Tuple{Union{Missing, String}, Bool}}(("a", true))

or a Tuple

In [352]:
Tuple(x[1, cols])
Out[352]:
("a", true)

Working with a collection of rows of a data frame¶

You can use eachrow to get a vector-like collection of DataFrameRows

In [353]:
df = DataFrame(reshape(1:12, 3, 4), :auto)
Out[353]:
34 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3x4
Int64Int64Int64Int64
114710
225811
336912
In [354]:
er_df = eachrow(df)
Out[354]:
34 DataFrameRows
Rowx1x2x3x4
Int64Int64Int64Int64
114710
225811
336912
In [355]:
er_df[1]
Out[355]:
DataFrameRow (4 columns)
Rowx1x2x3x4
Int64Int64Int64Int64
114710
In [356]:
last(er_df)
Out[356]:
DataFrameRow (4 columns)
Rowx1x2x3x4
Int64Int64Int64Int64
336912
In [357]:
er_df[end]
Out[357]:
DataFrameRow (4 columns)
Rowx1x2x3x4
Int64Int64Int64Int64
336912

As DataFrameRows objects keeps connection to the parent data frame you can get the columns of the parent using getproperty

In [358]:
er_df.x1
Out[358]:
3-element Vector{Int64}:
 1
 2
 3

Flattening a data frame¶

Occasionally you have a data frame whose one column is a vector of collections. You can expand (flatten) such a column using the flatten function

Only one row¶

only from Julia Base is also supported in DataFrames.jl and succeeds if the data frame has only one row, in which case it is returned.

In [363]:
df = DataFrame(a=1)
Out[363]:
11 DataFrame
Rowa
Int64
11
In [364]:
only(df)
Out[364]:
DataFrameRow (1 columns)
Rowa
Int64
11
In [365]:
df2 = repeat(df, 2)
Out[365]:

Rowa
Int64
11
21
In [366]:
only(df2)

3523
4624
5missing99

Rules for the on keyword argument:

  • a single Symbol or string if joining on one column with the same name, e.g. on=:id
  • a Pair of Symbols or string if joining on one column with different names, e.g. on=:id=>:id2
  • a vector of Symbols or strings if joining on multiple columns with the same name, e.g. on=[:id1, :id2]
  • a vector of Pairs of Symbols or strings if joining on multiple columns with different names, e.g. on=[:a1=>:a2, :b1=>:b2]
  • a vector containing a combination of Symbols or strings or Pair of Symbols or strings, e.g. on=[:a1=>:a2, :b1]

Standard joins: inner, left, right, outer, semi, anti¶

matchmissing keyword argument¶

In general you have three options how missing values are handled in joins that are handled by matchmisssing kewyowrd argument value as follows:

  • :error: throw an error if missings are encountered (this is the default)
  • :equal: assume misssing values are equal to themselves
  • :notequal: assume misssing values are not equal to themselves (not available for outerjoin)

Here are some examples comparing the options:

In [441]:
df1 = DataFrame(id=[1, 2, missing], x=1:3)
Out[441]:
32 DataFrame
Rowidx
Int64?Int64
111
222
3missing3
In [442]:
df2 = DataFrame(id=[1, missing, 3], y=1:3)
Out[442]:
32 DataFrame
Rowidy
Int64?Int64
111
2missing2
333
In [443]:

Since DataFrames.jl 1.3 you can do an efficient left join of two data frames in-place. This means that the left data frame gets updated with new columns, but the columns that exist in it are not affected. This operation requires that there are no duplicates of keys in the right data frame that match keys in left data frame:

Additional notes:

  • select! and transform! perform operations in-place
  • The general syntax for transformation is source_columns => function => target_column
  • if you pass multiple columns to a function they are treated as positional arguments
  • ByRow and AsTable work exactly like discussed for operations on data frames in 05_columns.ipynb
  • you can automatically groupby again the result of combine, select etc. by passing ungroup=false keyword argument to them
  • similarly keepkeys keyword argument allows you to drop grouping columns from the resulting data frame

It is also allowed to pass a function to all these functions (also - as a special case, as a first argument). In this case the return value can be a table. In particular it allows for an easy dropping of groups if you return an empty table from the function.

If you pass a function you can use a do block syntax. In case of passing a function it gets a SubDataFrame as its argument.

Here is an example:

In [510]:
combine(groupby(x, :id)) do sdf
    n = nrow(sdf)
    n < 25 ? DataFrame() : DataFrame(n=n) # drop groups with low number of rows
end
Out[510]:
32 DataFrame
Rowidn
CharInt64
1a28
2b25
3c28

You can also produce multiple columns in a single operation, e.g.:

In [511]:
df = DataFrame(id=[1,1,2,2], val=[1,2,3,4])
Out[511]:

Int64Int64

    groupby(:id)

you can transpose a data frame using permutedims:

In [531]:
df = DataFrame(reshape(1:12, 3, 4), :auto)

permutedims(df)

4101112

df.names = ["a", "b", "c"]

using PooledArrays

Performance tips¶

Access by column number is faster than by name¶

In [536]:
x = DataFrame(rand(5, 1000), :auto)
@btime $x[!, 500];
@btime $x.x500;

  1.700 ns (0 allocations: 0 bytes)
  9.409 ns (0 allocations: 0 bytes)

When working with data DataFrame use barrier functions or type annotation¶

In [537]:
using Random
function f_bad() # this function will be slow
    Random.seed!(1); x = DataFrame(rand(1000000,2), :auto)
    y, z = x[!, 1], x[!, 2]
    p = 0.0
    for i in 1:nrow(x)
        p += y[i]*z[i]
    end
    p
end

@btime f_bad();
# if you run @code_warntype f_bad() then you notice
# that Julia does not know column types of `DataFrame`

  134.286 ms (5999012 allocations: 122.06 MiB)
In [538]:
# solution 1 is to use barrier function (it should be possible to use it in almost any code)
function f_inner(y,z)
   p = 0.0
   for i in 1:length(y)
       p += y[i]*z[i]
   end
   p
end

function f_barrier() # extract the work to an inner function
    Random.seed!(1); x = DataFrame(rand(1000000,2), :auto)
    f_inner(x[!, 1], x[!, 2])
end

using LinearAlgebra
function f_inbuilt() # or use inbuilt function if possible
    Random.seed!(1); x = DataFrame(rand(1000000,2), :auto)
    dot(x[!, 1], x[!, 2])
end

@btime f_barrier();
@btime f_inbuilt();

  7.622 ms (34 allocations: 30.52 MiB)
  6.872 ms (34 allocations: 30.52 MiB)
In [539]:
# solution 2 is to provide the types of extracted columns
# it is simpler but there are cases in which you will not know these types
# This example  assumes that you have DataFrames master at least from August 31, 2018
function f_typed()
    Random.seed!(1); x = DataFrame(rand(1000000,2), :auto)
    y::Vector{Float64}, z::Vector{Float64} = x[!, 1], x[!, 2]
    p = 0.0
    for i in 1:nrow(x)
        p += y[i]*z[i]
    end
    p
end

@btime f_typed();

  7.549 ms (34 allocations: 30.52 MiB)

In general for tall and narrow tables it is often useful to use Tables.rowtable, Tables.columntable or Tables.namedtupleiterator for intermediate processing of data in a type-stable way.

Consider using delayed DataFrame creation technique¶

also notice the difference in performance between copying vs non-copying data frame creation

In [540]:
function f1()
    x = DataFrame([Vector{Float64}(undef, 10^4) for i in 1:100], :auto, copycols=false) # we work with a DataFrame directly
    for c in 1:ncol(x)
        d = x[!, c]
        for r in 1:nrow(x)
            d[r] = rand()
        end
    end
    x
end

function f1a()
    x = DataFrame([Vector{Float64}(undef, 10^4) for i in 1:100], :auto) # we work with a DataFrame directly
    for c in 1:ncol(x)
        d = x[!, c]
        for r in 1:nrow(x)
            d[r] = rand()
        end
    end
    x
end

function f2()
    x = Vector{Any}(undef, 100)
    for c in 1:length(x)
        d = Vector{Float64}(undef, 10^4)
        for r in 1:length(d)
            d[r] = rand()
        end
        x[c] = d
    end
    DataFrame(x, :auto, copycols=false) # we delay creation of DataFrame after we have our job done
end

function f2a()
    x = Vector{Any}(undef, 100)
    for c in 1:length(x)
        d = Vector{Float64}(undef, 10^4)
        for r in 1:length(d)
            d[r] = rand()
        end
        x[c] = d
    end
    DataFrame(x, :auto) # we delay creation of DataFrame after we have our job done
end

@btime f1();
@btime f1a();
@btime f2();
@btime f2a();

  29.334 ms (1949524 allocations: 37.40 MiB)
  31.231 ms (1949724 allocations: 45.03 MiB)
  2.438 ms (624 allocations: 7.66 MiB)
  4.798 ms (824 allocations: 15.30 MiB)

You can add rows to a DataFrame in place and it is fast¶

In [541]:
x = DataFrame(rand(10^6, 5), :auto)
y = DataFrame(transpose(1.0:5.0), :auto)
z = [1.0:5.0;]

@btime vcat($x, $y); # creates a new DataFrame - slow
@btime append!($x, $y); # in place - fast

x = DataFrame(rand(10^6, 5), :auto) # reset to the same starting point
@btime push!($x, $z); # add a single row in place - fast

  10.860 ms (210 allocations: 38.16 MiB)
  1.410 s (17 allocations: 672 bytes)
  741.722 ns (16 allocations: 256 bytes)

Allowing missing as well as categorical slows down computations¶

In [542]:
using StatsBase

function test(data) # uses countmap function to test performance
    println(eltype(data))
    x = rand(data, 10^6)
    y = categorical(x)
    println(" raw:")
    @btime countmap($x)
    println(" categorical:")
    @btime countmap($y)
    nothing
end

test(1:10)
test([randstring() for i in 1:10])
test(allowmissing(1:10))
test(allowmissing([randstring() for i in 1:10]))

Int64
 raw:
  4.435 ms (7 allocations: 7.63 MiB)
 categorical:
  13.891 ms (4 allocations: 688 bytes)
String
 raw:
  47.168 ms (4 allocations: 528 bytes)
 categorical:
  43.831 ms (4 allocations: 688 bytes)
Union{Missing, Int64}
 raw:
  8.042 ms (4 allocations: 560 bytes)
 categorical:
  20.999 ms (1000004 allocations: 30.52 MiB)
Union{Missing, String}
 raw:
  28.114 ms (4 allocations: 528 bytes)
 categorical:
  35.964 ms (1000004 allocations: 30.52 MiB)

Possible pitfalls¶

Know what is copied when creating a DataFrame¶

In [560]:
x = DataFrame(rand(3, 5), :auto)
Out[560]:
35 DataFrame
Rowx1x2x3x4x5
Float64Float64Float64Float64Float64
10.3116520.5935460.9154340.08417850.499355
20.2425920.07579840.1310660.9780160.14911
30.4468260.2913150.697490.04617870.123832
In [561]:
y = copy(x)
x === y # not the same object
Out[561]:
false
In [562]:
y = DataFrame(x)
x === y
Out[562]:
false
In [563]:
any(x[!, i] === y[!, i] for i in ncol(x)) 
# the columns are also not the same
Out[563]:
false
In [564]:
y = DataFrame(x, copycols=false)
x === y
Out[564]:
false
In [565]:
all(x[!, i] === y[!, i] for i in ncol(x)) 
# the columns are the same
Out[565]:
true
In [566]:
x = 1:3; y = [1, 2, 3]; df = DataFrame(x=x,y=y) 
# the same when creating data frames using kwarg syntax
Out[566]:
32 DataFrame
Rowxy
Int64Int64
111
222
333
In [567]:
y === df.y 
# different object
Out[567]:
false
In [568]:
typeof(x), typeof(df.x) 
# range is converted to a vector
Out[568]:
(UnitRange{Int64}, Vector{Int64})
In [569]:
y === df[:, :y] 
# slicing rows always creates a copy
Out[569]:
false

you can avoid copying by using copycols=false keyword argument in functions.

In [570]:
df = DataFrame(x=x,y=y, copycols=false)
Out[570]:
32 DataFrame
Rowxy
Int64Int64
111
222
333
In [571]:
y === df.y # now it is the same
Out[571]:
true
In [572]:
select(df, :y)[!, 1] === y # not the same
Out[572]:
false
In [573]:
select(df, :y, copycols=false)[!, 1] === y # the same
Out[573]:
true

g = groupby(x, :id)

Single column selection for DataFrame creates aliases with ! and getproperty syntax and copies with :¶

In [579]:
x = DataFrame(a=1:3)
x.b = x[!, 1] # alias
x.c = x[:, 1] # copy
x.d = x[!, 1][:] # copy
x.e = copy(x[!, 1]) # explicit copy
display(x)
x[1,1] = 100
display(x)
35 DataFrame
Rowabcde
Int64Int64Int64Int64Int64
111111
222222
333333
35 DataFrame
Rowabcde
Int64Int64Int64Int64Int64
1100100111
222222
333333

When iterating rows of a data frame use eachrow to avoid compilation cost (wide tables), but Tables.namedtupleiterator for fast execution (tall tables)¶

this table is wide

In [580]:
df1 = DataFrame([rand([1:2, 'a':'b', false:true, 1.0:2.0]) for i in 1:900], :auto)
Out[580]:
2900 DataFrame

DataFramesMeta.jl - working on DataFrame¶

DataFramesMeta.jl provides a more terse syntax due to the benefits of metaprogramming.

# one option is to use a function that works on a single observation and broadcast it
myfun(a, b) = a > 6 && b == 4 ? "yes" : "no"

In [625]:
# or you can use @eachrow macro that allows you to process DataFrame rowwise
@eachrow df begin
   @newcol :x::Vector{String}
    :x = :a > 6 && :b == 4 ? "yes" : "no"
end

11113no
12124yes

You can also use eachrow from DataFrames to perform the same transformation. However @eachrow will be faster than the operation below.

In [627]:
df2 = copy(df)
df2.x = Vector{String}(undef, nrow(df2))
for row in eachrow(df2)
   row[:x] = row[:a] > 6 && row[:b] == 4 ? "yes" : "no"
end
df2
